3) Data pipeline design

3.1 Choose indicators (feature set)

Start with ~6–12 indicators spanning different domains:
	•	Economy: GDP per capita, inflation, unemployment
	•	Health: life expectancy, infant mortality
	•	Environment: CO₂ emissions per capita
	•	Education: school enrollment

(You can let the user select indicators at runtime, but also provide curated presets like “Development basics”, “Climate & energy”, etc.)

3.2 Build a “country × features” matrix for clustering

For a selected year (or “latest available”):
	1.	Pull each indicator series per country
	2.	Extract the value for the chosen year: if missing, optionally take the nearest year within a tolerance window (e.g., ±2 years)
	3.	Produce a dataframe like:

country_code | country_name | region | income_level | INDICATOR_1 | INDICATOR_2 | ...

3.3 Missing data strategy (user-selectable)

Offer 2–3 options:
	•	Drop countries with >X% missing
	•	Impute with median (per-indicator)
	•	KNN imputation (optional, heavier)

3.4 Scaling / transforms (important for clustering)

Most indicators are on wildly different scales:
	•	Default: Standardize features (z-score)
	•	Optional: log-transform for skewed indicators (GDP, population)

⸻

4) Clustering approach

Implement at least two algorithms:

4.1 K-means (fast, good baseline)
	•	User controls: K
	•	Show: elbow curve / silhouette score suggestion (optional)

4.2 Hierarchical clustering (interpretable)
	•	Linkage: ward/average
	•	User controls: number of clusters or distance threshold
	•	Bonus: dendrogram (optional)

(DBSCAN/HDBSCAN can be added later for “density” clusters, but start with K-means + hierarchical.)

4.3 Dimensionality reduction for visualization

For the 2D scatter:
	•	PCA (simple and fast)
	•	Optional later: UMAP for nicer separation (extra dependency)

Plot points colored by cluster; hover shows country + values.

